'''Yamada Uenoyama Kofun''' (山田上ノ山古墳) is an ancient {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Taishi, Osaka|ja|太子町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minamikawachi District|ja|南河内郡|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}}. It is a {{ill|Circular tumulus|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=draft}} and part of the {{ill|Shinga Valley Kofuns|ja|磯長谷古墳群|1=Isonokami Valley Kofun Group|12=draft}}.

The {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} has Historic Site1 it as the "'''Osaka Shinga Mausoleum'''" (大阪磯長陵), the mausoleum of the 36th Emperor {{ill|Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
The mound is located in southeastern Osaka Prefecture, at the foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|12=draft}}, where it was constructed on a hill extending westward from the mountain. In front of the hill lies the {{ill|Takenouchi Kaidō|ja|竹内街道|1=Takenouchi Kaidō|12=draft}}. In the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, it was referred to as the "Kitayama Mausoleum" and was also known as the "Uguisu Mausoleum" (鶯陵).<ref name="Taishi">{{ill|Taishi Town Homepage|ja|太子町ホームページ|12=draft}}</ref> The {{ill|Kawachi Meisho Zue|ja|河内名所図会|12=draft}} links this site to the "Uguisu Mausoleum" mentioned in {{ill|The Pillow Book|ja|枕草子|12=draft}}.<ref group="Note">Some sources attribute the "Uguisu Mausoleum" in {{ill|The Pillow Book|ja|枕草子|12=draft}} to {{ill|Uguisuzuka Kofun|ja|鶯塚古墳|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|12=draft}} (see "Uguisuzuka Kofun," {{ill|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|ja|日本歴史地名大系|12=draft}} 30 Nara Prefecture, Heibonsha, 1981).</ref> Currently, the tomb is under the management of the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}}, and no detailed investigations have been conducted.

The tumulus is circular, with a diameter of 32 meters, and faces southwest. While details of the burial facilities are unclear, the site is known for the {{ill|Sea Beast Grape Mirror|ja|海獣葡萄鏡|12=draft}} supposedly excavated from a surrounding satellite mound, though its exact location remains unknown. The {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} designates it as the tomb of the 36th Emperor {{ill|Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|12=draft}} (who passed away in {{ill|654|ja|654th year|12=draft}}). The modest size of the tumulus may reflect Emperor Kōtoku's adherence to the {{ill|Thin burial Decree|ja|薄葬令|12=draft}}.<ref name="Kotoku">{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, Hakuchi 5 (654), October 10 (Jinshi).</ref>

The Shinga Valley is home to other imperial tombs attributed to Emperors {{ill|Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yōmei|ja|用明天皇|12=draft}}, {{ill|Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft}}, and Prince {{ill|Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子|12=draft}}, collectively referred to as the "Umebachi Imperial Tombs."

== Interred Individual ==
The actual individual interred at Yamada Uenoyama Kofun is unknown. However, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} designates it as the mausoleum of the 36th Emperor {{ill|Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|12=draft}}.<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html Imperial Tombs] - {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}}.</ref><ref>{{NDLDC|1237123/12|title=Ryo Bo Yoran}} (Imperial Household Ministry, 1934).</ref> According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, Emperor Kōtoku passed away in the 10th month of Hakuchi 5 (654) and was buried at "Osaka Shinga Mausoleum" in the 12th month of the same year.<ref name="Kotoku"/> The {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft}}, compiled in the 10th century, describes this mausoleum as a "remote tomb" in {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|12=draft}}, with a precinct of 5 chō (approximately 545 meters) in both east-west and north-south directions, and three caretakers annually assigned to its maintenance.<ref name="Engishiki">{{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft}}, vol. 21, Ministry of Ceremonial.</ref> During the {{ill|Genroku era|ja|元禄|12=draft}} (1699), the tomb was officially identified as Emperor Kōtoku's mausoleum, and renovations were carried out in {{ill|1864|ja|元治元年|12=draft}}.

