The tumulus is circular, with a diameter of 32 meters, and faces southwest. While details of the burial facilities are unclear, the site is known for the {{ill|Sea Beast Grape Mirror|ja|海獣葡萄鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} supposedly excavated from a surrounding satellite mound, though its exact location remains unknown. The {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} designates it as the tomb of the 36th Emperor {{ill|Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (who passed away in {{ill|654|ja|654th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). The modest size of the tumulus may reflect Emperor Kōtoku's adherence to the {{ill|Thin burial Decree|ja|薄葬令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Kotoku">{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Hakuchi 5 (654), October 10 (Jinshi).</ref>

The Shinga Valley is home to other imperial tombs attributed to Emperors {{ill|Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yōmei|ja|用明天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Suiko|ja|推古天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and Prince {{ill|Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, collectively referred to as the "Umebachi Mausoleums."

== Interred Individual ==
The actual individual interred at Yamada Uenoyama Kofun is unknown. However, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} designates it as the mausoleum of the 36th Emperor {{ill|Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html Mausoleums] - {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref><ref>{{NDLDC|1237123/12|title=Ryo Bo Yoran}} (Imperial Household Ministry, 1934).</ref> According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Emperor Kōtoku passed away in the 10th month of Hakuchi 5 (654) and was buried at "Osaka Shinga Mausoleum" in the 12th month of the same year.<ref name="Kotoku"/> The {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, compiled in the 10th century, describes this mausoleum as a "remote tomb" in {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with a precinct of 5 chō (approximately 545 meters) in both east-west and north-south directions, and three caretakers annually assigned to its maintenance.<ref name="Engishiki">{{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, vol. 21, Ministry of Ceremonial.</ref> During the {{ill|Genroku era|ja|元禄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1699), the tomb was officially identified as Emperor Kōtoku's mausoleum, and renovations were carried out in {{ill|1864|ja|元治元年|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

