== Overview ==
The mound is located in southeastern Osaka Prefecture, at the foothills of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Nijō|13=User:Immanuelle/Futakami Mountain|qq=}}, where it was constructed on a hill extending westward from the mountain. In front of the hill lies the {{ill|Takenouchi Kaidō|ja|竹内街道|1=Takenouchi Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Kaidō|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Kaidō|qq=}}. In the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], it was referred to as the "Kitayama Mausoleum" and was also known as the "Uguisu Mausoleum" (鶯陵).<ref name="Taishi">{{ill|Taishi Town Homepage|ja|太子町ホームページ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishi Town Homepage|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}</ref> The {{ill|Kawachi Meisho Zue|ja|河内名所図会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawachi Meisho Zue|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} links this site to the "Uguisu Mausoleum" mentioned in [[:en:The Pillow Book|The Pillow Book]].<ref group="Note">Some sources attribute the "Uguisu Mausoleum" in [[:en:The Pillow Book|The Pillow Book]] to [[:en:Uguisuzuka Kofun|Uguisuzuka Kofun]] in [[:en:Nara (city)|Nara City]] (see "Uguisuzuka Kofun," {{ill|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|ja|日本歴史地名大系|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|qq=}} 30 Nara Prefecture, Heibonsha, 1981).</ref> Currently, the tomb is under the management of the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]], and no detailed investigations have been conducted.

The tumulus is circular, with a diameter of 32 meters, and faces southwest. While details of the burial facilities are unclear, the site is known for the {{ill|Sea-beast grape mirror|lt=Sea-beast grape mirror|lt=Sea Beast Grape Mirror|ja|海獣葡萄鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sea Beast Grape Mirror|qq=}} supposedly excavated from a surrounding satellite mound, though its exact location remains unknown. The [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]] designates it as the tomb of the 36th Emperor [[:en:Emperor Kōtoku|Kōtoku]] (who passed away in [[:en:654|654]]). The modest size of the tumulus may reflect Emperor Kōtoku's adherence to the {{ill|Thin burial Decree|ja|薄葬令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Thin burial Decree|qq=}}.<ref name="Kotoku">[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], Hakuchi 5 (654), October 10 (Jinshi).</ref>

The Shinga Valley is home to other imperial tombs attributed to Emperors [[:en:Emperor Bidatsu|Bidatsu]], [[:en:Emperor Yōmei|Yōmei]], [[:en:Empress Suiko|Suiko]], and Prince [[:en:Prince Shōtoku|Shōtoku]], collectively referred to as the "Umebachi Mausoleums."

== Interred Individual ==
The actual individual interred at Yamada Uenoyama Kofun is unknown. However, the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]] designates it as the mausoleum of the 36th Emperor [[:en:Emperor Kōtoku|Kōtoku]].<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html Mausoleums] - [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]].</ref><ref>{{NDLDC|1237123/12|title=Ryo Bo Yoran}} (Imperial Household Ministry, 1934).</ref> According to the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], Emperor Kōtoku passed away in the 10th month of Hakuchi 5 (654) and was buried at "Osaka Shinga Mausoleum" in the 12th month of the same year.<ref name="Kotoku"/> The [[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]], compiled in the 10th century, describes this mausoleum as a "remote tomb" in [[:en:Kawachi Province|Kawachi Province]], with a precinct of 5 chō (approximately 545 meters) in both east-west and north-south directions, and three caretakers annually assigned to its maintenance.<ref name="Engishiki">[[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]], vol. 21, Ministry of Ceremonial.</ref> During the [[:en:Genroku|Genroku era]] (1699), the tomb was officially identified as Emperor Kōtoku's mausoleum, and renovations were carried out in [[:en:1864|1864]].

